WinterAnon here. I got so good by doing things one sentence at a time.
It's simple, really.

Vary the sentinces.
This here is five sentences.
It can be kind of boring.
I mean, it's only five.

See that? I bet that you're already skimming it.
Check this out.
This is a varied sentience.
You can make the story seem more interesting.
It's as simple as that.
Vary the length.

Use descriptors.
Wet can be moist, slick, gushing.
Hot can be warm, burning, boiling.
Sometimes, you can combine things.
Warm + wet. Sweltering.
It conveys that the thing that you're talking about is both states.

Have characters talk naturally. This is the hardest part of any story. I find myself talking to myself in the eyes and mindset of every talking character in the scene. People are rude. They cut each other off, don't let others finish-
Just like this.
See?
Simple as that and you've shifted the eyes of the reader onto the interrupting party.
This is particularly useful if a character starts droning.
People don't usually talk about things that already passed.
Make a complement and stop.
Allow the other person to respond and then continue.

You can also completely change words to better fit what you're trying to say.
Her warm vagina lubricated my fingers as I rubbed. (Intentionally shit)
Her sweltering pussy gushed her juice as I teased and toyed with her clit.

See? A slight change in words and it becomes sexy.

Give it a try. Nothing to loose but some bandwidth.

One thing to worry about is actually the overuse of adverbs and adjectives. Too many or too much of a variety can be distracting. This is especially true when writing dialog, as there is the temptation to use lots of different verbs for "said" in order to add flavor or use a ton of adverbs tacked onto those verbs.
